<subSubSection id="BA23C30F2627F0CD7F2F90DE4265E4B9" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="875F655BBAFAF999C6CE406EFA73392E" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3C5B71923127D3D284DB5FDE4857258B" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">
This species is easily recognized by the color of the elytra (Figs 
<figureCitation id="8CB6A11CF8E65A25F4C06027B5AC0D5C" captionStart="Figures 1–5" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 5. Diplotaxis balam sp. nov. 1 male habitus, dorsal view 2 male habitus, lateral view 3 aedeagus, dorsal view 4 aedeagus, lateral view 5 female habitus. Scale bars: 1 mm (1, 2, 5); 0.5 mm (3, 4)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.993.49434.figures1-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/475352" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">1-2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="A9128737073F6CEE228FCEC6EBE784C9" captionStart="Figures 1–5" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 5. Diplotaxis balam sp. nov. 1 male habitus, dorsal view 2 male habitus, lateral view 3 aedeagus, dorsal view 4 aedeagus, lateral view 5 female habitus. Scale bars: 1 mm (1, 2, 5); 0.5 mm (3, 4)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.993.49434.figures1-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/475352" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">5</figureCitation>
): ground color yellow with black, irregular foveae distributed throughout entire surface. No other described species of this genus shows this color pattern.
</paragraph>
<caption id="D6555A5F19817A70ED81A0ADBC2E14F6" doi="10.3897/zookeys.993.49434.figures1-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/475352" pageId="0" pageNumber="35" start="Figures 1–5" startId="F1">
<paragraph id="345555F5F2061C4B1F583BDF824A7EA7" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis id="11B70F60702ED05F25164576FF6BDE90" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="35">Figures 1-5.</emphasis>
